{
  "result": "Every city has an hour when it feels honest. In mine, that hour is just before dawn, when the buses exhale at empty stops and bakery lights bloom one by one along the avenue. Street cleaners move like patient metronomes, brushing yesterday into neat piles, and windows begin to glow in stacked, uncertain patterns. Nobody is performing yet. Nobody is selling, persuading, or pretending to be late.\n\nI like to walk then, with a cup of coffee warming my hand and no destination pretending to be important. The river smells metallic and cold. Pigeons argue over invisible treasure. A man in a blue cap unlocks his flower stall and arranges tulips by color, as if he is tuning an instrument before a concert no one has announced.\n\nBy seven o\u2019clock the spell breaks. Delivery trucks growl, phones chirp, and everyone remembers their name tags. Still, that earlier hour lingers like a secret stitched inside the day. It reminds me that beneath schedules and headlines there is a softer rhythm: bread rising, sky lightening, strangers nodding to one another simply because they share the same thin line between night and morning.\n\nMaybe that is enough meaning for now\u2014not a grand revelation, just the daily proof that beginnings can happen quietly, and that quiet things are often the ones that last. Tomorrow I will forget this wisdom by lunchtime, but before sunrise it returns, clear as breath in winter air, and I believe, again, that moments can teach us how to live.",
